g.text: An exploration of modern compute platforms: FPGA, CPU, GPU, using OpenCL, OneMKL, CUDA, ARM & INTEL SIMD extensionsDespite the simplicity of convolution, it is a very prominent algorithms which many other vision algorithms build on. It is also an example which has the features of many vision algorithms, and so convolution would be a window into judging how vision algorithms in general can be implemented with performance in mind, over these various architectures. For this work I asked myself with the usual modern household devices (and an FPGA!), how fast can I get a 128x128 image convolved with a 3x3 filter? Somy devices where an Arty-7 FPGA board, a Dell XPS laptop and a Samsung galaxy note, where the smartphone and the laptop in fact have 2 possible chips for the task, the CPU and the GPU and I evaluated both. AlsoI implemented our test algorithm using ARM Neon Extensions and x86 AVX Extensions, which are architecture specific vector extensions promising higher performance for parallel tasks such as convolution.Iman Hosseini, NYU Center for Cybersecurity

To interface with the FPGAI implemented a UART module, and marshalled data back from the FPGA to my laptop through COM (Serial) port. UART is a rather slow serial port, but for timing, the time calculation is based on the number of clocks, and frequency, and not the transfer time (as it is done for other devices as well)FPGAdesignwasdoneusingSystemVerilogintheVivadoISE, which is the IDE by Xilinx which then synthesizes the Verilog code and programs the FPGA. The design used free IP cores by Xilinx for the BlockRAMimplementation.

DELL XPS & FPGAGALAXY NOTE S20I implemented a very simple algorithm: convolution of a 128x128 image with a 3x3 kernel on various platforms and for the devices I hadand we can see the timing results for them. The image tells a story about performance, but the effort is another story. In terms of developer experience, I rate them from easiest to hardest as: 1) Python 2) C 3) AVX 4) CUDA 5) MKL 6) FPGA and for the android device as: 1) OpenCV 2) Java 3) C 4) Neon 5*) OpenCL whichisnotsupportedbyGoogleandisrenderedimpossible.Themostdisappointingperformerwas Intel MKL, which was also hard to work with, and compiler instrinsicswhere surprisingly nice: thatisifthealgorithmisrelativelyeasylikehere,becauseasa project grows it is not so easy to debug and is very verbose, they are also portable across compilers (GCC and MSVC both support it). UsingAVXon x86 and Neon on ARM (vector instructions) called SIMD for Single Instruction Multiple Data, is one waytoachieveparallelism,whileCUDA(GPUsingeneral)achieveparallelismin a much wider factor, and the width issetperkernelfunction whenitislaunched.ForMLCPUs can’t come close to GPUs for training, yet they can be viable (through these vector extensions) for inference tasks, which are less intensive.
